TITLE: Basic MongoDB Connection with Mongoose
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates the minimum required code to connect to a local MongoDB database using Mongoose. Uses the default port 27017 and connects to a database named 'myapp'.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/docs/connections.md#2025-04-14_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
mongoose.connect('mongodb://127.0.0.1:27017/myapp');
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: MongoDB Connection with Authentication
DESCRIPTION: Shows the connection string format for MongoDB connections that require authentication, including username, password, host, port, database, and additional options.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/docs/connections.md#2025-04-14_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
mongoose.connect('mongodb://username:password@host:port/database?options...');
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Connecting to MongoDB with Mongoose
DESCRIPTION: Example of connecting to a MongoDB database using Mongoose's connect method.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-14_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
await mongoose.connect('mongodb://127.0.0.1/my_database');
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Accessing and Using Mongoose Models
DESCRIPTION: Examples of accessing, instantiating, and saving Mongoose models, as well as finding documents.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-14_snippet_7

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const MyModel = mongoose.model('ModelName', mySchema);

const instance = new MyModel();
instance.my.key = 'hello';
await instance.save();

await MyModel.find({});

const instance = await MyModel.findOne({ /* ... */ });
console.log(instance.my.key); // 'hello'
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Creating and Saving Documents in Mongoose
DESCRIPTION: Shows three different ways to create documents: using the new operator with save(), using the create() method, or using insertMany() for batch operations.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/docs/models.md#2025-04-14_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const Tank = mongoose.model('Tank', yourSchema);

const small = new Tank({ size: 'small' });
await small.save();

// or

await Tank.create({ size: 'small' });

// or, for inserting large batches of documents
await Tank.insertMany([{ size: 'small' }]);
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Mongoose Connection Event Listeners
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to set up event listeners for various connection states using mongoose.connection.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/docs/connections.md#2025-04-14_snippet_14

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
mongoose.connection.on('connected', () => console.log('connected'));
mongoose.connection.on('open', () => console.log('open'));
mongoose.connection.on('disconnected', () => console.log('disconnected'));
mongoose.connection.on('reconnected', () => console.log('reconnected'));
mongoose.connection.on('disconnecting', () => console.log('disconnecting'));
mongoose.connection.on('close', () => console.log('close'));

mongoose.connect('mongodb://127.0.0.1:27017/mongoose_test');
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Connecting to MongoDB using Mongoose in Node.js
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to include Mongoose in a Node.js project and establish a connection to a local MongoDB instance. It uses an async function to handle the connection process.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/docs/index.md#2025-04-14_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
// getting-started.js
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

main().catch(err => console.log(err));

async function main() {
  await mongoose.connect('mongodb://127.0.0.1:27017/test');

  // use `await mongoose.connect('mongodb://user:password@127.0.0.1:27017/test');` if your database has auth enabled
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Creating and Saving a User Document with Mongoose in TypeScript
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to create an interface for a user document, define a schema, create a model, connect to MongoDB, and save a new user. It showcases the basic workflow for using Mongoose with TypeScript.
SOURCE: https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/blob/master/docs/typescript.md#2025-04-14_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
import { Schema, model, connect } from 'mongoose';

// 1. Create an interface representing a document in MongoDB.
interface IUser {
  name: string;
  email: string;
  avatar?: string;
}

// 2. Create a Schema corresponding to the document interface.
const userSchema = new Schema<IUser>({
  name: { type: String, required: true },
  email: { type: String, required: true },
  avatar: String
});

// 3. Create a Model.
const User = model<IUser>('User', userSchema);

run().catch(err => console.log(err));

async function run() {
  // 4. Connect to MongoDB
  await connect('mongodb://127.0.0.1:27017/test');

  const user = new User({
    name: 'Bill',
    email: 'bill@initech.com',
    avatar: 'https://i.imgur.com/dM7Thhn.png'
  });
  await user.save();

  console.log(user.email); // 'bill@initech.com'
}
```

